    "message_1": "Suppose you have a table of data containing f(x) values of a function at four distinct data points (x0, f(x0)), (x1, f(x1)), (x2, f(x2)) and (x3, f(x3)). Use Lagrange polynomials to estimate the value of the function at x=1.5. Here are the four pairs of data points:\n<br>(0, 0), (1, 2), (2, 4), (3, 8)</br>",
    "message_2": "To estimate the value of the function at x=1.5 using Lagrange polynomials, we can use the following formula:\n\nf(x) = L(x) = f(x0) * L0(x) + f(x1) * L1(x) + f(x2) * L2(x) + f(x3) * L3(x)\n\nwhere Lk(x) is the k-th Lagrange polynomial given by:\n\nLk(x) = Π((x - xi) / (xk - xi)) for i=0,1,2,3 and i≠k\n\nGiven the data points (0, 0), (1, 2), (2, 4), and (3, 8), we can calculate the Lagrange polynomials for x=1.5:\n\nL0(1.5) = ((1.5 - 1) * (1.5 - 2) * (1.5 - 3)) / ((0 - 1) * (0 - 2) * (0 - 3)) = (0.5 * -0.5 * -2.5) / (6) = 0.104167\n\nL1(1.5) = ((1.5 - 0) * (1.5 - 2) * (1.5 - 3)) / ((1 - 0) * (1 - 2) * (1 - 3)) = (1.5 * -0.5 * -2.5) / (-2) = 0.9375\n\nL2(1.5) = ((1.5 - 0) * (1.5 - 1) * (1.5 - 3)) / ((2 - 0) * (2 - 1) * (2 - 3)) = (1.5 * 0.5 * -1.5) / (2) = -0.28125\n\nL3(1.5) = ((1.5 - 0) * (1.5 - 1) * (1.5 - 2)) / ((3 - 0) * (3 - 1) * (3 - 2)) = (1.5 * 0.5 * -0.5) / (6) = -0.020833\n\nNow, we can calculate the estimated value of the function at x=1.5:\n\nf(1.5) = L(1.5) = 0 * L0(1.5) + 2 * L1(1.5) + 4 * L2(1.5) + 8 * L3(1.5) = 0 + 2 * 0.9375 + 4 * (-0.28125) + 8 * (-0.020833) = 1.875 - 1.125 - 0.166667 = 0.583333\n\nSo, the estimated value of the function at x=1.5 using Lagrange polynomials is approximately 0.583333."
